  <div class="article-header">
    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag" style="background:#FAC775;color:#412402;">Reaction of the week</span>
      <span class="tag" style="background:#E1F5EE;color:#085041;">Redox Reaction</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="article-title">The Thermite Reaction: Chemistry's Most Spectacular Fire Show</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Discover how aluminum powder and rust create one of chemistry's most intense reactions, producing molten iron at temperatures hot enough to melt steel.</p>
    <div class="meta">8 min read · Includes video · 3 research links</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">The reaction</div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#AFA9EC;">2 Al + Fe₂O₃</span>
    <span class="eq-arrow">→</span>
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#9FE1CB;">Al₂O₃ + 2 Fe + heat</span>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">Imagine mixing two common powders – aluminum dust and rust – and igniting them to create a reaction so intense it produces molten iron at over 2500°C (4500°F). This is the thermite reaction, one of chemistry's most dramatic demonstrations of oxidation-reduction reactions and energy release.</p>
  <p class="body-text">The thermite reaction occurs when powdered aluminum acts as a reducing agent, stealing oxygen atoms from iron oxide (rust). This electron transfer releases an enormous amount of energy because aluminum has a much stronger attraction for oxygen than iron does. The result? Pure molten iron and aluminum oxide, along with enough heat to weld railroad tracks or cut through steel.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">Why is the thermite reaction so energetic?</div>
    <div class="callout-text">The secret lies in the difference in oxidation potentials between aluminum and iron. Aluminum is much more reactive than iron, so when it "steals" oxygen from iron oxide, it releases about 850 kJ of energy per mole – enough to heat the products to their melting points and beyond.</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">What makes this reaction particularly fascinating is its practical applications. Thermite welding has been used since the early 1900s to join railroad tracks, repair large steel structures, and even in military applications. The reaction is self-sustaining once started and doesn't require an external oxygen source, making it incredibly useful in situations where traditional welding isn't feasible. However, the extreme temperatures and safety hazards mean this reaction should only be performed by trained professionals with proper safety equipment.</p>

